'''Rafael López Nussa''' (1885–1943) was a [[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]] [[physician]] and [[public servant]].  In 1916 López Nussa performed the first heart surgury operation in Puerto Rico.

==Early Years==
López Nussa was born in [[Mayaguez, Puerto Rico]], on 22 February 1885. He was the son of Ramon B. López and Micaela Nussa.<ref name=AlbumHistorico277>Luis Fortuño Janeiro. ''Album Histórico de Ponce (1692-1963).'' Page 277. (Ponce, Puerto Rico: Imprenta Fortuño. 1963.)</ref>

==Education==
After completing his schooling years and graduating from high school in Puerto Rico, López Nussa entered college and graduated with a degree in medicine from [[Georgetown University]] in 1906. He graduated with specialization from the [[New York University School of Medicine|New York Post Graduate Medical School]] in 1913, and from the [[University of Illinois College of Medicine|Chicago Laboratory of Surgical Technique]] in 1916.<ref name= AlbumHistorico277/>

==Career==
He returned to Puerto Rico and acted as [[medical director]] at the [[Hospital Tricoche]] in [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]] from 1907 to 1920.<ref name=AlbumHistorico277/> He represented Puerto Rico at the International Congress for Medicine in [[London]] in 1913.<ref>[http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2299907/ ''Seventeenth International Congress of Medicine (London, 1913).''] British Medical Journal. 1913 June 28; 1(2739): 1375–1376. Retrieved 18 March 2012.</ref>  In 1916 he performed a delicate cardiac surgical procedure at Hospital Tricoche in Ponce; it is so registered in the records of the [[Puerto Rico Medical Association]] as the first such procedure performed in Puerto Rico.<ref name=AlbumHistorico277/>

In 1918 he took a position at the [[Hospital San Lucas]] as surgeon and medical director.  He was also a surgeon at Ponce's Hospital de Distrito, and was also a medical consultant for the new [[University of Puerto Rico School of Medicine|Escuela de Medicina Tropical]] in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].<ref name=AlbumHistorico277/>

==Political and other activities==
In 1915, Lopez Nussa was one of the co-founders of the Puerto Rico National Guard.<ref>Luis Fortuño Janeiro. ''Album Histórico de Ponce (1692-1963).'' Page 263. Ponce, Puerto Rico: Imprenta Fortuño. 1963.</ref> In 1928, he was president of Ponce School Board. He was also president of the Ponce Rotary Club, vicepresident of the Puerto Rico Medical Association, member of the American Board of Surgeons, and the physician of the [[Parque de Bombas|Ponce Firefighters Corps]].<ref name=AlbumHistorico277/> In 1930, he presided over the medical group that traveled to the [[Dominican Republic]] to care for victims of [[1930 Dominican Republic hurricane|San Zenon]] tropical storm.<ref name=AlbumHistorico277/> In 1934, Lopez Nussa formed part of the welcoming committee for the arrival of U.S. President [[Franklyn Delano Roosevelt]] and his wife to Ponce.<ref>Luis Fortuño Janeiro. ''Album Histórico de Ponce (1692-1963).'' Page 146. Ponce, Puerto Rico: Imprenta Fortuño. 1963.</ref>

==Death==
Lopez Nussa, died in San Juan on 3 March 1943.

==Legacy==
There is a [[Public housing in Puerto Rico|public housing]] developments in [[Ponce, Puerto Rico|Ponce]] named after Lopez Nussa.<ref>[http://www.visitaaponce.com/Eventos/Mensaje%20de%20Presupuesto%202011.pdf ''MENSAJE DE PRESUPUESTO: AÑO FISCAL 2011-2012. Page 29.''] Hon. María “Mayita” Meléndez Altieri, Mayor. Autonomous Municipality of Ponce. Ponce, Puerto Rico. 30 May 2011. Retrieved 18 March 2012.</ref><ref>Sunny A. Cabrera Salcedo. ''Hacia un Estudio Integral de la Toponimia del Municipio de Ponce, Puerto Rico.'' Ph. D. dissertation. May 1999. University of Massachusetts Amherst. Graduate School. Department of Spanish and Portuguese. Page 182.</ref> He is also recognized as one of Ponce's greatest physicians<ref>[http://www.travelponce.com/Medicine.html ''Medicine.''] TravelPonce Retrieved 18 March 2012.</ref> at the [[Tricentennial Park (Ponce, Puerto Rico)|Park of the Illustrious Ponce Citizens]]. In San Juan, the municipal hospital is named in his honor.<ref>[http://www.hud.gov/local/pr-vi/homeless/healthcare.cfm ''Health Care Resources: Puerto Rico/VirginIslands.''] U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development. Retrieved 18 March 2012.</ref>  There is also a school named in his memory.<ref>[http://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?HiGrade=-1&IncGrade=-1&LoGrade=-1&SchoolType=1&SchoolType=2&SchoolType=3&SchoolType=4&Search=1&SpecificSchlTypes=all&State=72&SchoolPageNum=22&ID=720003001040 ''School Name: DR. Rafael Lopez Nussa.''] National Center for Education Statistics. U.S.Department of Education. Retrieved 18 March 2012.</ref>

